metadata.name: LANDSCAPE_CITY_BUILDING #35
metadata.description:
Tokyo has many buildings.
In Shibuya, the buildings themselves are displays, shining brightly even at night.
It is dazzling.
Buildings seen from train windows have changed since I was in the countryside.
Electric wires are also entangled with them.
I am one of the insects attracted by the glare.
I must make a landscape painting before I sober up.

metadata.name: Holy Moly #37
metadata.description:
The idea for this project came from a common drawing exercise where different shapes and shading are used to create the illusion of depth. Here I'm using four layers containing various types of holes. Some are recognizable primitive shapes but others are organic in form or distorted. There are ten features reported that affect the character of each output.

To change the resolution:
1. Click on the image
2. Use the keys 2-8 to change resolution, '2' will produce a 2000 x 2000 image (default), '3' a 3000 x 3000 image etc
3. Once generated press 'S' to save as a png

Jeff Clark
December 2022
--------------------------
All drawing and geometric code created by Jeff Clark using vanilla javascript except for:

- perlin.js from https://codepen.io/sixsided/pen/emxxea.js

metadata.name: Expanse #16
metadata.description:
land • generative audio • sky

Audio: [a] to allow audio.
Interact: [i] for more details, including URL parameters

A meditation on the meeting point of sky and land, inspired by the salt marshes near my home, but with an other-worldly influence. I'm always keenly aware, perhaps as we all are, that humanity's hold on the planet is slipping. In time we may be forced to explore new avenues for survival, but then the dream of seeking a new world is nothing new. And then, pessimistic as it may be, perhaps one day we shall be forced to simply survey a desolate and scarred Earth, and admit that despite all they did, humanity got it wrong.

The piece takes place in a widescreen canvas, resolutely sticking to a monochrome rendition except in a vanishingly-rare coloured version, expected to appear in around 2.5% of pieces. Colour is interesting, of course, so there are extensive options for playing with various colour modes—details available on pressing 'I' in full-screen mode.
However…  white on black, or black on white; the main piece relies on density, dot-size and texture for effect, whilst the aspect ratio not only suits modern computer screens, but allows for the expansive nature of the horizon to stretch forth.

The heart of the piece is the landscape itself, a small section of a very large circle. The OpenProcessing sketch ‘Landscape Curvature’ documents my initial steps on the piece, a fumbling return to trigonometry.

Curvature is thoroughly explored: a larger circle produces a nearly-horizontal line, with perpendicular features, whilst a smaller circle produces extremes of curvature, and divergingly-angled additions. Additionally, a negatively-large circle can be generated, inverting the horizon as though viewed through a fish-eye lens. Features sway towards each other, and cluster dangerously close in the centre of the piece.

Although the piece is considered finished after three-hundred and sixty frames, I like the render process to be as much a point of interest as the finished piece, and so the landscape is formed progressively: thousand upon thousands of tiny points maniuplated and added to the piece over time.

This artwork renders fastest and most accurately in Google Chrome.

metadata.name: Triangle Subdivisions #160
metadata.description:
A study on geometric triangle subdivisions resulted in this artwork.
Only 638 bytes of JavaScript are needed to create a variety of different subdivisions (and no libraries are used). 

One tile will be generated for every byte of code.  

An article about this technique can be seen here:
https://josvromans.com/blog/2021/1/triangle-subdivisions/

metadata.name: THE END #109
metadata.description:
An ode to our short lives & our even shorter years, a lingering feeling of it having escaped through our grasp as we were just about to comprehend its meanings, shoved into another cycle of life and death. Unlike our cosmos both above and below, the universe and the microscopic world - omnipresent and continuous; time almost feels like a prison on land, a boat without a sail in the sea, an astronaut without a spaceship - a binding of our mind and behaviour. As if we were too afraid to face the eternal chain of feedback loop that engulfs us all. So as this year comes to an end and another one begins, here is my last piece.

This year was full of surprises for all of us, packed with floods, fires, hurricanes, wars and amazing new discoveries! This piece was inspired by the constant yearning to escape into the endless space. And as James Web Telescope keeps discovering new stuff out there, it makes me question - is the big bang real? Or has it always been like this? Are we very close to discovering something new? What if just like time, space was just another loop? How do the different dimensions intertwine with each other? Despite all hardships, this year end seems to bring about hope - hope for a better exciting future. Hope that we might survive our doomsday. Hope that we might actually be ready to face the endless void beyond earthly time and space. 

And with that said I hereby introduce my last piece for 2022, the cosmic fidget spinner with melancholic 90s generative audio! 

Interactivity: 

Press M for the audio (Proceed with caution I am not really a musician)
Press P to check performance 
Press S to save a 1920x1920 screenshot 
Click and drag over the artwork to play around with the cosmic sculpture 

In case you are on the phone, you can use the invisible menu button at the top right corner of the frame for accessing all of the above functionality!    

And best of luck for 2023!

Jaalibandar '22

metadata.name: Vanishing #87
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstract generative work that uses shapes, colors, and texture to depict the finitude of everything we see and are. As if we threw these shapes into smoke or fog, they get lost after a while. The symbolism of vanishing is also the texture with which I tried to depict the old canvas, which decays, cracks, and fades after time. 

Why we were happier as children? Thinking back to your childhood, didn't you live in the moment and didn't any day seem long? With each decade, time seemed to speed up. We become more aware of time and forget to live in the moment. Enjoy everything while it lasts, enjoy the forms until they disappear in fog or smoke, enjoy the painter's canvas until it disappears, and enjoy life, because it is finite.

Options:

- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 'd' to save a hi-res PNG image

Created using p5.js
Bajiru, March 2023.

metadata.name: Whisper #288
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: Tears of the Mountains #54
metadata.description:
The "Tears of the Mountains" is a generative art collection that showcases emotions ranging from tears of happiness to boundless optimism. Inspired by Edgar Payne, I infused my own creative perspective into this art piece, giving consideration to important components such as value, composition, the rule of thirds, and perspective.

This series was crafted with pure code using p5.js.

Created by Costa C. | OneRocket.nft

------------------------------------
Press ‘s’ to save the current image.

In live view:
Add "&size=high" at the end of the url to get 4K size of image.
Add "&size=full" at the end of the url to get 8K size of image.

metadata.name: Abstract Maelstroms #5
metadata.description:
The "maelstrom" word is a rare word in English and it evokes that strong vortexes can be revived in generative art concept with 2d. The shadows used in this piece are also a rare application despite their limited area of usage.

There are approximately 1,000,000 - 1,800,000 lines in each canvas. The process of the scene may change between 10 and 30 seconds depending on the power of your machine. Therefore, you can prefer to use a PC or laptop to get quick and better results.

metadata.name: Pearls #98
metadata.description:
Pearls is a generative minimal artwork made with 100% code in p5js.

This algorithm places perfectly round pearls into multiple stacked grids and connects them in a pleasing way. The small grids lead to interesting emerging patterns. Some see faces and fish, others see ancient hardware and elephants, and some just enjoy the minimal simplicity.

-- controls (in live view)
s: to save the current image
a: to play a small animation

-- some attributes
layout: 2x2 to 34x34
palette: genuary, monochrome red & purple, night
mode: ink, walk
bias: central, north, east, south, west
density: sparse, middle, dense
symmetry: none, vertical, horizontal, point
layer: 2 to 6
